Pre-heat your #grill{} to medium-high setting. Take the @pork medallion{2} and pop them on a #plate{}. Drizzle over a glug of @olive oil{1%glug}, season with a pinch of @salt{} and sprinkle over half of the @Malay curry powder{½}. Rub the oil and seasoning into both sides of your pork. Keep to one side.

Wash your hands and get on with the rest of your prep. Cut the @onion{1} in half through the root. Peel and then slice into thin half moon shapes. Remove the top and bottom from the @carrot{1} and then peel. Chop your carrot into small chunks (ideally ½cm). Peel the @garlic clove{1} and then grate (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one).

Put a large #frying pan{} (with a #lid{}) on medium-high heat. Add a splash of oil and your onion and carrot. Cook for ~{4-5%minutes} stirring frequently until your onion is soft. Next, add your remaining Malay spice mix, garlic and the @water{200%ml} to your pan.

Cook for another ~{1%minute} then add the @chicken stock pot{1}. Stir well and bring to the boil. Make sure your stock pot is dissolved before covering your pan with a lid. Reduce the heat to low and leave your veggies to bubble away for ~{10%minutes}. Remove the lid after ~{5%minutes} and cook your veggies uncovered for ~{5%minutes}.

While your veggies cook, pop your pork onto a foil lined #baking tray{} and grill for ~{12-14%minutes}. Turn after ~{6-7%minutes} to make sure it cooks evenly.

> The pork is cooked when the centre is no longer pink.

Pop a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add the @nigella seeds{½%tsp}. Cook for ~{1%minute} or until your nigella seed flavoured oil smells fragrant. Remove them to a #bowl{} and mix in the @olive oil{1%glug}. Season with @salt{} and keep the nigella seed flavoured oil to one side. We will use it for the chapatis.

Reheat the now empty frying pan over high heat and when the pan is hot, add the @super soft tortillas with whole wheat{4} one at a time. Cook for ~{30%seconds} to ~{1%minute} on each side and remove to a plate.

> You want the tortillas to scorch slightly.

Drizzle some of your nigella seed flavoured oil over each one as you pop them onto the plate. These are your chapatis.

Drain the @green lentils{1%packet} in a #colander{} and rinse under cold water. When your veggies have softened, add the @baby spinach{1%bag} to the pan. Cook for ~{2%minutes} to wilt your spinach. Next, stir in your lentils and the @crème fraîche{1} and bring to the boil. Check the seasoning and add salt and @ground black pepper{} to taste if necessary.

When your pork is cooked leave it to rest for a few mins on a #chopping board{}, before slicing each steak into six pieces.

Serve your creamy lentils in #bowls{} and place your pork on top. Chop your chapatis into six pieces each and serve alongside. Enjoy!